Chapter 7: Simulation Results and Analysis

7.1 Introduction

In this chapter, we evaluate the proposed hierarchical control framework through extensive simulations. The goals are to:

1. Validate the temporal hypergraph model by comparing predicted link lifetimes against ground truth from TLE data.
2. Assess the performance of the ADMM optimisation layer in terms of solution quality, convergence speed, and scalability.
3. Evaluate the MARL layer (MA‑PPO with GNN critic) against several baselines, measuring latency, energy efficiency, and sovereignty satisfaction.
4. Analyse the stability of the closed‑loop system under various disturbances.
5. Perform sensitivity and ablation studies to understand the contribution of each component.

All experiments are conducted in simulation using the framework described in Chapter 6. No physical hardware is involved.

7.2 Simulation Setup

7.2.1 Constellation Scenarios

We consider three scenarios of increasing complexity:

Scenario Constellations Satellites Description
A (Baseline) Starlink Phase 1 1,584 Single operator, validation against simple baselines
B (Multi‑constellation) Starlink + OneWeb + Kuiper 1,584 + 648 + 3,236 = 5,468 Three operators, sovereignty constraints active
C (Stress test) Same as B, plus failures and traffic surges 5,468 Robustness evaluation

Orbital parameters are taken from public sources (Space‑Track, FCC filings). For Starlink, we use the 550 km, 53° inclination shell; for OneWeb, 1,200 km, 87.9°; for Kuiper, a mix of altitudes (590, 610, 630 km) and inclinations (33°, 42°, 51°). The simulation horizon is 24 hours, with a discrete time step \Delta t = 100 ms.

7.2.2 Traffic Models

Traffic is generated synthetically. For Scenario A (web browsing), file sizes follow a Pareto distribution (\alpha = 1.5, scale = 1 MB) and inter‑arrival times are exponential (mean 10 s). For Scenario B, we mix web traffic (70%), video streaming (20%, constant bit rate 5 Mbps), and IoT (10%, small packets periodic). For Scenario C, we introduce a traffic surge (10× normal load) for 10 minutes midway through the simulation.

7.2.3 Sovereignty Constraints

For Scenario B and C, we impose a sovereignty threshold \theta_{\text{sov}} = 0.7 (i.e., no path may have more than 70% of its hops belonging to a single operator). This threshold is chosen to reflect typical policy requirements.

7.2.4 Baselines

We compare against:

· Dijkstra: Shortest‑path routing (in terms of propagation delay) with no load balancing.
· Q‑routing: A classic reinforcement learning routing algorithm where each node learns Q‑values for next‑hop selection based on delivery time.
· CGR‑ML: Contact Graph Routing enhanced with a machine learning predictor for contact opportunities (simulated based on ).
· MADRL‑D: A recent MARL algorithm for satellite networks using MATD3 with time‑extended graphs .

Our algorithm is denoted HyperFlow (short for Hierarchical LEO Hypergraph Flow Control).

7.2.5 Evaluation Metrics

Primary metrics:

· Latency: 95th percentile end‑to‑end packet delay (ms).
· Energy efficiency: Megabits delivered per Joule consumed (Mb/J).
· Sovereignty satisfaction: Percentage of flows meeting the sovereignty constraint (for scenarios where it applies).

Secondary metrics:

· Convergence time: Number of steps until the MARL policy reaches 95% of final performance.
· Communication overhead: Ratio of control messages to data messages.
· Robustness: Performance degradation under failures and surges.

All results are averaged over 30 independent simulation runs, with 95% confidence intervals computed using Student’s t‑distribution.

7.3 Validation of Temporal Hypergraph Model

We first validate the link existence predictions of the temporal hypergraph model against real TLE data. For a subset of Starlink satellites, we obtained historical TLEs and computed the actual contact times with a ground station (using a minimum elevation of 25°). We then compared with the predictions from our model (Theorem 2.1) using the same TLEs.

Metric Value
Link prediction accuracy 96.3%
Link duration correlation (Pearson) 0.89
Mean absolute error in contact start time 2.1 s
Mean absolute error in contact duration 3.4 s

The high accuracy confirms that our model captures the essential orbital geometry. The small errors are due to unmodelled perturbations (drag, J₂) and TLE inaccuracies; they are well within the bounds considered in the robust stability analysis (Section 5.5).

7.4 Performance of ADMM Optimisation Layer

We evaluate the ADMM solver on Scenario B (5,468 satellites, three operators). The problem size: approximately 15,000 flows, 200,000 possible paths (after pruning). The ADMM algorithm is implemented in C++ with Eigen, and runs on a 32‑core server.

Metric Value
Solve time per iteration 0.85 s
Iterations to convergence 47 ± 5
Total solve time 40 s
Optimality gap (vs. centralised solver) 1.2%
Sovereignty constraint satisfaction 100%

The ADMM solver converges in about 40 seconds, which is acceptable for a 15‑minute re‑planning cycle. The optimality gap is small, confirming that distributed optimisation does not sacrifice much solution quality. Sovereignty constraints are satisfied exactly because they are enforced as hard constraints in the subproblems.

