7.8 Statistical Significance

All comparisons are tested using paired t‑tests (30 runs per condition). The improvements of HyperFlow over the best baseline (MADRL‑D) are statistically significant with p < 0.01 for all primary metrics. Effect sizes (Cohen’s d) are large (d > 0.8).

7.9 Summary

This chapter has presented a comprehensive simulation‑based evaluation of the proposed hierarchical control framework. Key findings:

· The temporal hypergraph model accurately predicts link dynamics.
· The ADMM optimisation layer provides near‑optimal, sovereignty‑compliant flow allocations with fast convergence.
· The MARL layer (MA‑PPO with GNN critic) outperforms state‑of‑the‑art algorithms, achieving 24.8% lower latency and 26.6% higher energy efficiency on a single‑operator scenario, while maintaining 99.2% sovereignty satisfaction in multi‑operator settings.
· The system is robust to failures and traffic surges, recovering quickly and preserving constraint satisfaction.
· Ablation studies confirm the importance of each component.
· The system scales efficiently to 10,000 satellites, meeting real‑time requirements.

These results validate the theoretical claims and demonstrate the potential of the proposed architecture for practical deployment.

